{"title":"Leveraging LLM Reasoning Enhances Personalized Recommender Systems","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Zero-shot LLMs often struggle to make accurate, personalized rating predictions because preferences are subjective and dispersed across rich user histories and item metadata.","method":"Use zero-shot chain-of-thought prompting that presents the entire interaction context in natural language—preamble, sequential user history with reviews and ratings, and new item metadata—and explicitly asks the model to reason before outputting a 1–5 rating. This CoT setup yields consistent gains over direct prediction and naive baselines, and ablations show that removing user reviews (and ratings) severely degrades performance, highlighting the importance of rich textual feedback for eliciting useful reasoning."},{"problem":"Running large LLMs with CoT at inference is expensive; smaller models often lack reasoning ability for personalized recommendation tasks.","method":"Distill reasoning from a stronger LLM by sampling multiple diverse reasoning–rating pairs per user–item at different decoding temperatures, then fine-tune smaller sequence-to-sequence models (e.g., Flan-T5) to generate reasoning followed by the rating using these sampled reasons plus gold rating labels as targets. Optional filters compare the large model’s predicted ratings to ground truth (5-class, binary, 1-off). Fine-tuning with reasoning consistently outperforms rating-only training, scales with model size, benefits from multiple reasoning paths, and shows domain-dependent effects of filtering."},{"problem":"There is no scalable, objective way to evaluate the quality of subjective, personalized reasoning in recommender systems without curated gold explanations or human raters.","method":"Introduce Rec-SAVER, an automatic reasoning evaluation pipeline that (1) generates post hoc explanations conditioned on user history, item metadata, and the ground-truth rating, (2) removes rating-leaking phrases, and (3) self-verifies each explanation by asking the LLM to predict the rating from it, retaining only explanations that reproduce the gold label as verified references. Reasoning outputs from target models are then scored against this verified pool with BLEU/ROUGE/METEOR/BERTScore. Human studies show these metrics correlate with coherence and faithfulness, and the self-verification step improves correlations, enabling reference-free, scalable reasoning assessment."}]}
